dom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bolhay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon and Cornwall): from Bowhay Farm in Exminster (Devon) or Bowhayes Farm in Culmstock (Devon). The placenames derive from Middle English <i>boue</i>, <i>bogh</i> ‘bow, arch, bend’ + <i>wei</i> ‘road, way’ (Old English <i>boga</i>, <i>weg</i>)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hamlin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, from the Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Hamelin</i>, a double diminutive of <i>Hamo</i> (see   Hammond  ).","French: variant of   Hamelin   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","Americanized form of Finnish <b>Hämäläinen</b> (see   Hamalainen  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Hamling","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Hamlin  ."]},{"name":"Hammond","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Ha(i)mon</i>, the oblique case form of the ancient Germanic <i>Ha(i)mo</i>, a short form of various compound names beginning with <i>haim</i> ‘home’. It frequently developed excrescent <i>-d</i>, giving <i>Hamond</i>, <i>Haimund</i>, and <i>Hawmond</i>. Alternatively, the name could derive from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamund</i> (Old Norse <i>Hámundr</i>, composed of the elements <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’), which may have been used in Normandy and in 12th-century eastern England, but the former explanation is more likely. The surname was sometimes confused with   Almond   and   Ammon  .","English: in the Bradford area of Yorkshire, the name is a shortened form of <b>Ormondroyd</b>, formerly <i>Hamondesrode</i>, from a lost place in Birstall (Yorkshire), named with the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Hamon</i> (1 above) + Middle English <i>roid</i>, a southern Yorkshire pronunciation of Old English <i>rod</i> ‘clearing’.","Irish: generally an importation from England, but occasionally an adopted name for <b>Mac Ámoinn</b>, see   McCammon  ."]},{"name":"Hamalainen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Finnish Reino, Pekka, Aimo, Arvi, Jukka, Jussi, Olavi, Pirjo, Raija, Timo, Wiljo.","Finnish (<b>Hämäläinen</b>): habitational name for someone from Häme province, in central Finland. This is a well-established Finnish surname dating back to the 16th century. Compare   Hamlin  ."]},{"name":"Hamlen","meanings":["Found as a baptismal name. There does not appear to be any etymological connexion between this name and Hamnet. According to some the name in Hamlet's country was pronounced Amlet, and signifies 'madman' but no etymology has been suggested for such rendering. Amlet is the same name as Amleth, mentioned in the Danske Historic of Saxo Grammaticus, and Amlethus, King of Denmark and Sweden, found in Zedler's Lexicon. The name is from the Old German amal-laut, distinguished for spotlessness."]},{"name":"Hamblin","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Hamlin  ."]},{"name":"Hamlyn","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Hamlin  .","Americanized form of Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Hamburger  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Hamlin Bolhay was born about 1145, in England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Mrs HAMELYN BOLHAY. He died before 1241."},"et":{"Abt 1145–Bef 1241":"umbes 1145–enne 1241","–Female":"Surnud","1170–1241":"1170–1241","1145–1241":"1145–1241","Bef 1241":"enne 1241","Abt 1145":"umbes 1145","1145":"1145","1241":"1241","Abt 1170":"umbes 1170","1170":"1170","Blackborough, Devon, England":"Blackborough, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1145–Bef 1241":"noin 1145–ennen vuotta 1241","–Female":"Kuollut","1170–1241":"1170–1241","1145–1241":"1145–1241","Bef 1241":"ennen vuotta 1241","Abt 1145":"noin 1145","1145":"1145","1241":"1241","Abt 1170":"noin 1170","1170